metadata.name: Recursive Ruins #244
metadata.description: Amidst the terrain of a newly discovered planet, explorers stumble upon a remarkable find: a landscape dotted with crumbling ruins boasting a distinct mathematical order. Within these ancient relics, primitive geometric shapes abound, alongside inscriptions in an enigmatic script. Yet, it is the presence of recursive substructures that confounds researchers, their origins steeped in the  mystery of time. The identity of these ancient architects remains elusive.

metadata.name: Translucent Prismic Colour-scapes (16:9) #12
metadata.description:
Randomly constructed, translucent prismic colour-scapes at a fixed 16:9 ration (2048px x 1152px).

I've used a set window size so the preview and outcome remain the same. Some previous projects had an issue with window resizing and preview rendering changing the final project outcome.

metadata.name: CA Panico #129
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: Incomplete Convergence #351
metadata.description:
Cutting an optimization process short can lead to interesting results. This series builds on the earlier Sneronoi series but doesn't attempt to run to full convergence. Images are generated by gradient descent and the optimization process is shown as an animation. Each piece is considered final when the animation stops.

There are ten different color palettes, each with four different options for background colors. There are also different shapes drawn in the background and different modes in which the foreground and the background are blended together. In combination, these options result in a wide range of distinct visual outputs. Made with D3.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png (4000x4000).

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #972
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: System β #164
metadata.description:
α -> β is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

_

press [2] -> β⁰　 
press [3] -> β¹
